  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 18.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Brethren, the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with your spirit.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Amen",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἡ χάρις τοῦ Κυρίου ἡμῶν Ἰησοῦ Ξριστοῦ μετὰ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τοῦ πνεύματος ὑμῶν ἀδελφοί Ἀμήν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with your spirit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "brethren. Amen.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"The grace of Jesus Christ\" denotes his Saviour's loving-kindness, not only effectual in making a guilty soul acceptable to God through his atonement, but also in purifying it from sin, enduring it with spiritual strength, and securing its final salvation. The pre-eatery imperative \"be,\" which, of course, is to be supplied, clothes a friendly wish in the pious form of a prayer. \"With,\" the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "μετὰ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " which, in the Septuagint, represents the Hebrew '",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "im",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", meaning \"present to help,\" is illustrated by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 21:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ruth 2:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 6:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 1:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; 28:90; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 3:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 16:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"With your spirit,\" here, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Philippians 4:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Philemon 1:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 4:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", replaces the \"with you,\" which is the form in which the farewell greeting is commonly couched; as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 16:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ephesians 6:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. There is no polemical reference whatever in the substitution; rather it is an affectionate amplification or intensification of the kindly wish or blessing, the outcome of affectionate yearning, after the stern rebukes which he had felt himself compelled to address to them. It expresses his desire that Christ's grace might be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "very",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " near to them - near to the most intimate and most controlling part of their nature. The singular \"spirit\" is conjoined with the plural pronoun \"your,\" as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 8:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 6:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (\"your body\"); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 5:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"your spirit and soul and body.\" The word \"brethren\" is added last of all, as it were in caressing affectionateness, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Philemon 1:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The final \"Amen\" seals the true earnestness and the devotional spirit of the benediction. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Galatians 6:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The grace, etc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The same form of benediction occurs Plm 1:25.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Brethren",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Rev. rightly puts the word at the end of the verse. The position is unusual. It would seem as if Paul intended to close this severe letter with an assurance that the \"foolish Galatians\" were still his brethren: They are addressed as \"brethren,\" Galatians 4:12; Galatians 5:11; Galatians 6:1. Comp. 1 Corinthians 16:24. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Rev. rightly puts the word at the end of the verse. The position is unusual. It would seem as if Paul intended to close this severe letter with an assurance that the \"foolish Galatians\" were still his brethren: They are addressed as \"brethren,\" ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Galatians 4:12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Galatians 5:11",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Galatians 6:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Corinthians 16:24",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
